01:35:42.260 --> 01:35:49.132
We’ll put you into groups of four.
Mike, Maggie, Paul, Connie...

01:35:49.340 --> 01:35:53.253
Girls downstage, boys upstage.

01:35:59.900 --> 01:36:02.619
Connie, smile bigger,
if you gotta fake it.

01:36:02.820 --> 01:36:06.210
- Tapping is not my strong point.
- What?

01:36:06.420 --> 01:36:11.414
- Tapping’s not my strongest point.
- I see that.

01:36:17.260 --> 01:36:19.649
I"II be right back.

01:36:30.540 --> 01:36:34.658
- Don’t move him.
- Larry. Call Dr. Rhodes.

01:36:37.300 --> 01:36:43.057
- His knee was operated last year.
- Don’t move it.

01:36:44.740 --> 01:36:47.573
I just twisted it.

01:36:47.780 --> 01:36:50.658
Does anyone have Valium?

01:36:53.220 --> 01:36:55.859
It’s already swelling.

01:36:57.180 --> 01:36:59.853
You’re gonna be okay, Paul.

01:37:00.060 --> 01:37:03.530
Should we give him that?
We don’t know what’s wrong.

01:37:03.740 --> 01:37:06.937
I’ve had three already, since lunch.

01:37:07.140 --> 01:37:09.938
It’s just a muscle relaxer.

01:37:10.140 --> 01:37:15.294
Rhodes is waiting in Emergency
at St. Joseph’s.

01:37:16.580 --> 01:37:20.698
You’re going to be all right. Rhodes
is the best knee doctor in town.

01:37:20.900 --> 01:37:24.495
- Paul, I’ve got your bag!
- Good luck.

01:37:24.700 --> 01:37:27.453
Call me from the hospital.

01:37:47.380 --> 01:37:51.373
Do you ever think about what
you’ll do when you stop dancing?

01:37:51.580 --> 01:37:54.014
Me?

01:37:56.260 --> 01:37:58.899
Real life, I guess.

01:37:59.100 --> 01:38:02.058
Getting married, having babies?

01:38:03.860 --> 01:38:06.738
Going off my diet.

01:38:11.980 --> 01:38:16.132
Mark, do you want spend your life
dancing in a chorus?

01:38:16.340 --> 01:38:20.253
I just want to get in one.

01:38:20.460 --> 01:38:25.454
You don’t remember, but we were in
a chorus together a 100 years ago.

01:38:25.660 --> 01:38:30.370
- Of course I remember.
- You were a rotten dancer.

01:38:30.580 --> 01:38:35.415
Why do you think I became
a choreographer?

01:38:35.620 --> 01:38:39.454
- How have you been, Sheila?
- Since then, I don’t know...

01:38:39.660 --> 01:38:44.415
Good. Terrific. So-so...

01:38:44.620 --> 01:38:47.532
I actually found
the glass slipper once.

01:38:47.740 --> 01:38:52.211
It fit, but then it broke.

01:38:52.420 --> 01:38:58.575
I have a daughter. She’s nine.
She loves me a lot, hates me a lot...

01:38:59.380 --> 01:39:04.534
And... God help her,
she wants to be a dancer.

01:39:06.060 --> 01:39:12.499
What’s so wrong about that?
How can anybody want anything else?

01:39:15.460 --> 01:39:20.534
I used to stand outside the stage door
and watch the girls come out, -

01:39:20.740 --> 01:39:25.336
- thinking, "God, can anything
like that ever happen to me?"

01:39:25.540 --> 01:39:28.771
Now I meet somebody and they say:

01:39:28.980 --> 01:39:34.259
"Wow, you dance on Broadway?
You got somewhere. "

01:39:50.700 --> 01:39:54.773
- Hell of a day, huh?
- Yeah...

01:39:54.980 --> 01:40:00.100
A few months ago, the night before
I was to audition for another show, -

01:40:00.300 --> 01:40:04.532
- I had a kind of breakdown.

01:40:04.740 --> 01:40:09.814
I started crying and I couldn’t stop
for two weeks.

01:40:10.020 --> 01:40:15.253
I just got out of hospital.
The doctor said it was too soon.

01:40:15.460 --> 01:40:17.928
But I did.

01:40:18.140 --> 01:40:22.930
And now, even if I lose, I won.

01:40:29.260 --> 01:40:31.820
Hell of a day.

01:40:50.980 --> 01:40:54.052
- Line "em up, Zach?
- Yeah.

01:40:54.260 --> 01:40:57.297
Everybody on the line.

01:41:26.740 --> 01:41:31.097
Before we start eliminating...

01:41:31.300 --> 01:41:36.135
You’re all terrific.
And very special.

01:41:36.340 --> 01:41:39.138
I wish I could hire you all.

01:41:39.340 --> 01:41:42.935
Will the following people
please step forward.

01:41:45.460 --> 01:41:46.859
Judy.

01:41:51.540 --> 01:41:53.019
Don.

01:41:58.220 --> 01:42:01.018
Greg.

01:42:04.060 --> 01:42:06.699
Sheila.

01:42:12.300 --> 01:42:15.417
Al.

01:42:17.620 --> 01:42:19.929
Diana.

01:42:20.140 --> 01:42:24.213
Excuse me...
Diana, will you get back in line?

01:42:27.260 --> 01:42:29.535
Kristine.

01:42:32.500 --> 01:42:35.139
Connie.

01:42:38.060 --> 01:42:40.335
Maggie.

01:42:45.700 --> 01:42:49.454
Front line, thank you very much.
I’m sorry.

01:43:18.620 --> 01:43:23.216
Rehearsals begin September 22nd.
We rehearse for six weeks -

01:43:23.420 --> 01:43:28.414
- with a two-week tryout,
either in Boston or Philadelphia.

01:43:28.620 --> 01:43:34.331
The New York opening will be
some time mid-January.

01:43:34.540 --> 01:43:40.012
Prepare to sign the standard minimum
contract with a six-month rider.

01:43:42.340 --> 01:43:47.414
Check with Larry
for your costume measurings.

01:43:51.300 --> 01:43:57.455
Do not, I repeat, do not change
your hairstyle or color.

01:43:57.660 --> 01:44:03.895
I’m happy to be working with you.
It’s going to be very exciting.

01:44:12.700 --> 01:44:15.339
Thank you very much.

01:44:26.380 --> 01:44:30.931
Dick! That’s it. Thanks a lot.

01:44:52.460 --> 01:44:54.928
Cassie...

01:45:07.700 --> 01:45:10.339
How you dress!

01:45:15.860 --> 01:45:20.297
You can get arrested for wearing
those colors.

01:45:57.540 --> 01:46:00.816
<i>One singular sensation</i>

01:46:01.020 --> 01:46:04.376
<i>Every little step she takes</i>

01:46:04.580 --> 01:46:07.697
<i>One thrilling combination</i>

01:46:07.900 --> 01:46:11.495
<i>Every move that she makes</i>

01:46:11.700 --> 01:46:18.617
<i>One smile and suddenly
nobody else will do</i>

01:46:18.820 --> 01:46:25.498
<i>You know you’ll never be lonely
with you know who.</i>

